insights: Process runs on a bi-weekly schedule: Tuesdays (covering Sat-Tue deliveries) and Fridays (covering Wed-Fri deliveries)

Process requires manual coordination between operations team and engineering team via Slack
Weekly tabs are created to track historical reset requests

results.purpose: Pet food subscription pricing strategy and model for different product plans (Fresh, Mixed, Topper, Dry, Air Dried) with competitive benchmarking and margin optimization
key_data_points: Max freezer fill: 1/3 of small NYC apartment freezer
Fresh plan: Match TFD prices (excluding shipping)
Topper plan: 55-62.5% of Fresh price for 50% of product
PC2 margins and ROI are key performance metrics

entities.name: TFD (The Farmer's Dog)
entities.context: Primary competitor benchmark for Fresh plan pricing

entities.name: Ollie
entities.context: Competitor for Fresh plan pricing comparison

entities.name: Pantry Fresh
entities.context: Competitor reference point for Mixed plan positioning

entities.name: TPT
entities.context: Company creating this pricing model (likely The Pet Table or similar)

insights: Pricing strategy is hierarchical: Fresh (highest) → Mixed → Topper → Dry/Air Dried (lowest)
Fresh plan serves as the 'headline price' anchor for all other plans
Company prioritizes larger dogs due to higher ROI potential
Pricing model went through 6-step methodology: import costs → benchmark → scenarios → smoothing → margin checks → price matching
Key architectural principle: same quantity of food should always cost the same across SKUs
Price testing focuses on three areas: architecture issues, competitor positioning, and customer segment optimization
Shipping is charged separately but waived for first order to reduce acquisition friction
Company is willing to sacrifice some price-per-pound consistency to maintain target margins (PC2)
